  "prompt": "What people from other countries think about Indian Caste system?",
  "response": "Perspectives on the Indian caste system from people in other countries can vary widely and are often influenced by their own cultural backgrounds, levels of awareness, and the diversity of their interactions with Indian society. Some common viewpoints include:\n\n1. **Criticism and Condemnation**: Many people from around the world criticize the caste system as a form of social inequality and discrimination. They often equate it with other forms of systemic oppression and draw parallels to racial discrimination in their own countries. The rigid stratification and history of discrimination against lower castes are frequently condemned.\n\n2. **Historical and Cultural Curiosity**: Some individuals approach the caste system from an academic or cultural perspective, seeking to understand its historical roots, its evolution, and its impact on Indian society. They may study how the caste system compares to other social hierarchies and systems of stratification around the world.\n\n3. **Misunderstanding or Oversimplification**: Due to a lack of comprehensive understanding, some people might have a simplified or stereotyped view of the caste system. They might see it as an antiquated system that doesn't have relevance in modern India, or they might generalize the experiences of all Indian people based on limited information.\n\n4. **Recognition of Complexity and Change**: There is an awareness among some that the caste system is complex and not monolithic. They recognize that India has undergone significant social changes, and legal measures have been implemented to combat caste-based discrimination. Additionally, they understand that the experience of the caste system can vary greatly depending on region, economic status, and individual agency.\n\n5. **Empathy and Support for Change**: Some people express empathy towards those who have been adversely affected by the caste system and support movements that aim to dismantle caste-based discrimination. They may also support international and local NGOs working on social justice and equality in India.\n\nIt\u2019s important to note that these perspectives are not exhaustive and can be influenced by media representations, personal interactions with Indian individuals, and broader geopolitical relationships. Additionally, as with any social issue, perspectives can evolve over time with greater awareness and understanding.",
